*****
[1] Case update
Date: Sat 4 Jun 2011
Source: BBC [edited]
http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13652817


European health officials say there are signs that the outbreak of a
deadly strain of _E. coli_ [O104:H4] is stabilizing. They said that
despite nearly 200 new cases in Germany, the center of the outbreak,
in the 1st 2 days of June 2011, infection rates were dropping.
However, one doctor cautioned: "It may be less, but it's not over
yet."

At least 18 people have died, and 1836 have been infected by the bug
since it was 1st detected on 1 May 2011. Most of those affected are in
Germany. German clinics have been appealing for blood donations as
doctors have had to perform blood transfusions in severe cases.

The Robert Koch Institute (RKI), Germany's national disease centre,
said on Friday [3 Jun 2011] that in the previous 2 days, there had
been 199 new cases of the outbreak, bringing to 1733 the number of
infections. The WHO said a further 103 people in 12 other countries
had been sickened by the bug; all but one had recently traveled to or
from northern Germany.

Reinhard Brunkhorst, president of the German Nephrology Society, told
reporters there were some signs that the outbreaks were slowing. He
said hospitals in northern Germany, the epicenter of the scare, had
seen fewer new infections being reported each day.

"There is no reason for hysteria, because it's not spreading, and
it's not increasing; it's decreasing," he said. But he also stressed
that it was too early for doctors to positively say the end of the
outbreak was in sight.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[More "points on the curve" are needed to confirm the downtrend in
cases, which should be occurring unless a continuing source of
infection is present. With a fresh produce source, without continuing
exposure of newer produce, this is predictable. With a meat source
which can be frozen and stored, the cases can more easily continue. -
Mod.LL]

******
[2] Restaurant investigation
Date: Sat 4 Jun 2011
Source: MSNBC [edited]
http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/43278122/ns/health-food_safety/


German scientists are looking for clues about the source of the
killer _E. coli_ [O104:H4] in a restaurant in the northern German town
of Lubeck after 17 people fell ill after eating there, a newspaper
reported on Sat 4 Jun 2011.

The 17 people who fell sick included a group of German tax officials
and tourists from nearby Denmark, the Lubecker Nachrichten newspaper
said.

"The restaurant is not to blame," said Werner Solbach, a
microbiologist at University Medical Center Schleswig-Holstein.
"However, the supply chain could give us important clues about how the
pathogen was passed along."

A German woman, one of the tax officials at the Lubeck restaurant,
died after contracting the _E. coli_ strain. Many who contracted _E.
coli_ have developed hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), a potentially
deadly complication that can affect the kidneys.

The group of German tax officials, who were attending a tax union
event, ate at the restaurant on 13 May 2011, the union head told
Reuters on Sat 4 Jun 2011. The Lubecker Nachrichten newspaper said all
victims ate there between 12-14 May 2011.

The German news magazine Focus reported on Sat 4 Jun 2011 that
officials are pursuing a theory in which the outbreak started at the
beginning of May 2011 in Hamburg, as people started becoming ill after
a week, consistent with _E. coli's_ incubation period.

[Byline: Brian Rohan]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
