[In a specific restaurant setting, it may be easier to assess which
food vehicle may be implicated as the source. ProMED awaits more
information regarding this investigation. - Mod.LL]

******
[3] Antimicrobial Issue
Date: Fri 3 Jun 2011
Source: Nature [edited]
http://blogs.nature.com/news/2011/06/europes_e_coli_outbreak_time_f.html


As enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ [O104:H4] continues to cause an
unprecedented number of life-threatening infections in Europe,
American medics are questioning Germany's approach to the outbreak,
according to the New York Times.

It reports that "the accepted medical wisdom in the USA is that EHEC
_E. coli_ infections should not be treated with antimicrobial agents
at all," and it quotes Phillip Tarr, pediatrician at Washington
University, as saying that treating patients with antimicrobial agents
to which the infecting bacteria are resistant is especially dangerous,
as this provides the infecting strain with a competitive advantage.
The NYT article also says that antibiotics can increase the chances of
kidney failure, although it does not explain how. (The reason is that
antibiotics prompt the bacteria to release more Shiga toxin, the
chemical responsible for the damage to blood vessels in the kidneys
that leads to renal failure during severe EHEC infections.)

Although you wouldn't realize it from the NYT article, German doctors
and microbiologists are well aware of these important, but not novel,
considerations. The German health authorities have told the press and
the public from the outset that the bacteria show unusual
antimicrobial resistance characteristics, but they have continually
stressed that they were not using these agents to treat these
infections. The resistance genes provide useful information to
epidemiologists and microbiologists who are trying to trace the source
of the outbreak and understand the virulence of the bacteria.

The standard treatment for the severe diarrhea and kidney failure
that can result from EHEC infections is fluid replacement and
dialysis. But these traditional methods are simply not enough to save
the lives of many severely ill patients in this outbreak. Ten days
ago, German clinicians turned to a new monoclonal antibody therapy
called eculizumab. Jan Kielstein, nephrologist at the Hannover Medical
Clinic, says that 200 patients have now been treated with eculizumab,
with promising outcomes, although it is too early to definitively
align these recoveries with the drug.

In the past 2 days, however, some German hospitals have begun using
antimicrobial agent treatments. "After intense discussions, there has
been a decision to recommend antimicrobial agents in some cases under
tight regulation of patient responses," says Angelika Fruth from the
Robert Koch Institute, the federal agency responsible for disease
control.

The German Association of Infection Biology (DGI) released a
statement on the use of antimicrobial agents on 3 Jun 2011. It states
that the use of certain antibiotics associated with enhanced toxin
secretion (including fluoroquinolones and aminoglycosides) is still
not recommended for EHEC infections. But it advises that the
carbapenem family of antimicrobials may be used in patients showing
neurological complications and secondary infections. Kielstein says
that "in vitro tests show that this antibiotic is effective against
this _E. coli_ strain and that the bacteria do not produce more Shiga
toxin in response to it."

The DGI statement also states that targeted reduction of intestinal
bacteria with the antibiotic rifaximin is recommended in exceptional
cases of EHEC persistence.

The NYT article also quoted Timothy Jones, the state epidemiologist
in Tennessee, who said: "Having a strain that is virulent is not
unusual." There are indeed multiple strains of _E. coli_ that cause
infection in humans. But the number of cases of the life-threatening
complication hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS) that have arisen from
this outbreak is a dramatically higher proportion than usual.

[Byline: Marian Turner]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>



[Although the carbapenem family of antimicrobial agents (including
ertapenem, meropenem and imipenem) are often still active against
multidrug resistant Gram negative bacilli, they are penicillin-like
drugs that disrupt cell wall production and may well allow more toxin
to be released, not have more toxin produced. Rifaximin is a
non-absorbable rifamycin antimicrobial agent that is used for
traveler's diarrhea, and any role in EHEC disease is speculative.
Hopefully, the use of these agents is being monitored closely for
positive and negative effects. The humanized monoclonal antibody
eculizumab (directed against a complement component) is also being
studied. Since HUS generally resolves, it may be difficult to define
its role. - Mod.LL]
